00:13:21,967 --> 00:13:22,968
This is my son Frank.

264
00:13:22,968 --> 00:13:23,969
Oh, hi.

265
00:13:23,969 --> 00:13:24,970
He needs a black suit.

266
00:13:24,970 --> 00:13:26,472
Black suit...

267
00:13:26,472 --> 00:13:27,973
There was a death
in the family.

268
00:13:27,973 --> 00:13:29,475
My father, 85 years old,
war hero.

269
00:13:29,475 --> 00:13:31,477
Yeah?

270
00:13:31,477 --> 00:13:33,979
There's a funeral
this afternoon, military funeral

271
00:13:33,979 --> 00:13:35,981
planes flying overhead,
21-gun salute.

272
00:13:36,482 --> 00:13:37,483
Geez.

273
00:13:37,483 --> 00:13:39,485
Frank needs
to borrow a suit

274
00:13:39,485 --> 00:13:40,486
for a couple
of hours.

275
00:13:40,986 --> 00:13:43,489
I'm sorry, we don't loan suits,
and we're not open.

276
00:13:43,489 --> 00:13:44,990
Darcy... Darcy, please.

277
00:13:44,990 --> 00:13:46,992
(sighs) Come back.

278
00:13:46,992 --> 00:13:48,994
Darcy... is this yours?

279
00:13:48,994 --> 00:13:50,996
(jingles)

280
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:57,503
I just found it
in the parking lot.

281
00:13:57,503 --> 00:13:59,505
Uh-huh.

282
00:13:59,505 --> 00:14:02,007
It must've slipped
right off your neck.

283
00:14:04,009 --> 00:14:05,010
(tires screeching)

284
00:14:05,010 --> 00:14:07,012
Don't hit the curb.

285
00:14:09,014 --> 00:14:11,016
(brakes squeaking)

286
00:14:12,017 --> 00:14:13,519
Now get out,
walk around the back

287
00:14:14,019 --> 00:14:15,521
and hold the door open
for me.

288
00:14:18,524 --> 00:14:20,526
(car horn honks)

289
00:14:25,030 --> 00:14:26,031
All right.

290
00:14:26,532 --> 00:14:27,533
What's next?

291
00:14:27,533 --> 00:14:29,034
Okay, stop grinning.

292
00:14:29,034 --> 00:14:32,538
When I get inside, you go back
to the front seat and wait.

293
00:14:32,538 --> 00:14:35,040
Even if a cop comes
and writes you a ticket

294
00:14:35,040 --> 00:14:37,042
you don't move the car,
understood?

295
00:14:37,042 --> 00:14:39,044
Dad, wha-what's
all this for?

296
00:14:39,044 --> 00:14:41,046
You know why the Yankees
always win, Frank?

297
00:14:41,046 --> 00:14:42,548
'Cause they have
Mickey Mantle?

298
00:14:42,548 --> 00:14:44,550
No, it's 'cause
the other teams

299
00:14:44,550 --> 00:14:47,052
can't stop staring
at those damn pinstripes.

300
00:14:47,052 --> 00:14:48,053
Watch this.

301
00:14:48,053 --> 00:14:49,555
The manager
of Chase Manhattan Bank

302
00:14:49,555 --> 00:14:54,059
is about to open the
door for your father.

303
00:14:56,061 --> 00:14:58,063
Mr. Abagnale, um

304
00:14:58,063 --> 00:15:00,566
we don't usually
loan money to people

305
00:15:00,566 --> 00:15:02,568
who have unresolved business
with the IRS.

306
00:15:02,568 --> 00:15:04,570
That's a
misunderstanding.

307
00:15:04,570 --> 00:15:06,572
I hired the wrong
guy to do my books.

308
00:15:06,572 --> 00:15:08,073
A mistake, I...
anybody could make it.

309
00:15:08,073 --> 00:15:10,576
I just need you
guys to help me
weather the storm.

310
00:15:10,576 --> 00:15:13,078
Sir, you're being investigated
by the government

311
00:15:13,078 --> 00:15:15,080
for tax fraud.

312
00:15:15,080 --> 00:15:17,082
My store is a landmark
in New Rochelle.

313
00:15:17,082 --> 00:15:19,084
I have customers
all over New York.

314
00:15:19,084 --> 00:15:21,587
Well, you're not a customer
at Chase Manhattan.

315
00:15:21,587 --> 00:15:22,588
We don't know you.

316
00:15:22,588 --> 00:15:24,590
I'm sure your bank
in New Rochelle

317
00:15:24,590 --> 00:15:26,592
they know you,
they could help you out.

318
00:15:26,592 --> 00:15:28,093
My bank went
out of business.

319
00:15:28,093 --> 00:15:30,596
Banks like this one put
them out of business.

320
00:15:30,596 --> 00:15:32,598
Now, I know I made a
mistake, I admit that

321
00:15:32,598 --> 00:15:34,099
but these people want blood.

322
00:15:34,099 --> 00:15:35,100
They want my store.

323
00:15:35,100 --> 00:15:37,102
They've threatened
to put me in jail.

324
00:15:37,102 --> 00:15:39,104
(stammers)

325
00:15:39,104 --> 00:15:40,606
This is America, right?

326
00:15:40,606 --> 00:15:41,607
I'm not a criminal.

327
00:15:41,607 --> 00:15:43,108
I'm a Medal of Honor winner

328
00:15:43,108 --> 00:15:45,611
a lifetime member
of the New Rochelle Rotary Club.

329
00:15:46,111 --> 00:15:48,614
All I'm asking is for you
to help me beat these guys.

330
00:15:48,614 --> 00:15:51,617
It's not a question
of winning and losing.

331
00:15:51,617 --> 00:15:53,118
It's a question of risk.

332
00:15:53,118 --> 00:15:55,621
You're the largest
bank in the world.

333
00:15:55,621 --> 00:15:57,122
Where's the fu...

334
00:15:57,122 --> 00:16:00,125
Whe... Where's the risk?

335
00:16:05,130 --> 00:16:08,133
Dad, how could you just let him
take our car like that?

336
00:16:08,133 --> 00:16:10,135
He didn't take anything.
We took him.

337
00:16:10,135 --> 00:16:11,136
He overpaid by $500.

338
00:16:11,136 --> 00:16:14,640
Come on, Frank.

339
00:16:14,640 --> 00:16:16,141
Let's return the suit.

340
00:16:16,141 --> 00:16:18,143
(Paula sobbing)

341
00:16:24,149 --> 00:16:25,651
This place is good.

342
00:16:25,651 --> 00:16:27,152
It's small but, you know

343
00:16:27,653 --> 00:16:30,155
it's going to be
a lot less work.

344
00:16:30,155 --> 00:16:31,657
A lot less work for you.

345
00:16:31,657 --> 00:16:34,159
(jackhammer drilling
in distance)

346
00:16:42,668 --> 00:16:44,670
(keys clank)

347
00:16:54,680 --> 00:16:56,181
FRANK:
Hey, Dad.

348
00:16:56,181 --> 00:16:58,183
Hi.

349
00:17:01,687 --> 00:17:03,689
Where's your mother?

350
00:17:03,689 --> 00:17:04,690
I don't know.

351
00:17:04,690 --> 00:17:09,194
She said something
about going to look for a job.

352
00:17:10,696 --> 00:17:11,697
What's she gonna be

353
00:17:11,697 --> 00:17:13,699
a shoe salesman
at a centipede farm?

354
00:17:13,699 --> 00:17:14,700
(laughing)

355
00:17:15,200 --> 00:17:17,703
(both laughing)

356
00:17:19,705 --> 00:17:21,206
What are you doing?

357
00:17:21,206 --> 00:17:22,708
(both laughing)

358
00:17:22,708 --> 00:17:25,210
You want some pancakes?

359
00:17:25,210 --> 00:17:26,211
For dinner?

360
00:17:26,211 --> 00:17:28,213
On my son's
16th birthday?

361
00:17:28,213 --> 00:17:30,215
We're not gonna
eat pancakes.

362
00:17:32,718 --> 00:17:35,220
Come on, why are you
looking at me like that?

363
00:17:35,220 --> 00:17:36,722
You thought I forgot?

364
00:17:36,722 --> 00:17:39,725
I didn't think you forgot.
I opened a
checking account

365
00:17:39,725 --> 00:17:41,727
in your name.

366
00:17:41,727 --> 00:17:42,728
I put $25 in the account

367
00:17:42,728 --> 00:17:44,730
so you can buy
whatever you want.

368
00:17:44,730 --> 00:17:46,231
Don't tell your mother.

369
00:17:46,231 --> 00:17:47,232
I won't.

370
00:17:47,232 --> 00:17:48,233
Thanks, Dad.

371
00:17:48,233 --> 00:17:49,234
Yep.

372
00:17:49,234 --> 00:17:52,488
Didn't that bank turn you down
for a loan, though?

373
00:17:52,488 --> 00:17:54,239
Yes, they all
turned me down.

374
00:17:54,239 --> 00:17:55,741
(chuckles)

375
00:17:55,741 --> 00:17:57,743
Then why you opening a
banking account with them?

376
00:17:57,743 --> 00:18:00,245
Well, because one day,
you'll want something

377
00:18:00,245 --> 00:18:02,247
from these people--
a house, a car.

378
00:18:02,247 --> 00:18:05,250
They have all the money.

379
00:18:07,753 --> 00:18:10,756
There's 50 checks
there, Frank

380
00:18:10,756 --> 00:18:15,260
which means, from
this day on...

381
00:18:15,260 --> 00:18:17,763
you're in their
little club.

382
00:18:17,763 --> 00:18:21,266
I'm in their little club.

383
00:18:21,266 --> 00:18:23,268
You got that,
you got it all.

384
00:18:23,268 --> 00:18:27,773
It's even got
my name there, huh?

385
00:18:27,773 --> 00:18:28,774
To the moon.

386
00:18:28,774 --> 00:18:30,776
To the moon!

387
00:18:30,776 --> 00:18:33,779
To the moon.

388
00:18:33,779 --> 00:18:35,781
(bells tolling)

389
00:18:42,287 --> 00:18:45,290
See that?
It's just a school.

390
00:18:45,290 --> 00:18:46,792
No different
than Westbourne.

391
00:18:46,792 --> 00:18:50,796
Ma... you said you were
going to quit.

392
00:18:53,799 --> 00:18:57,302
Frankie, you don't have
to wear the uniform here.

393
00:18:57,302 --> 00:19:00,305
Why don't you take
off your jacket?

394
00:19:00,305 --> 00:19:03,308
I'm used to it.

395
00:19:03,308 --> 00:19:05,310
(indistinct conversation)

396
00:19:07,813 --> 00:19:08,814
Excuse me.

397
00:19:08,814 --> 00:19:09,815
Oh, yes?

398
00:19:09,815 --> 00:19:11,817
Do you know where
room 17 French is?

399
00:19:11,817 --> 00:19:13,819
GIRL:
Yeah, it's...

400
00:19:13,819 --> 00:19:15,320
(snickering)

401
00:19:19,324 --> 00:19:21,827
(school bell ringing)

402
00:19:21,827 --> 00:19:23,829
BOY:
But you frickin'
killed him.

403
00:19:23,829 --> 00:19:27,332
(loud indistinct conversation)

404
00:19:27,332 --> 00:19:29,334
You selling
encyclopedias?

405
00:19:29,334 --> 00:19:32,838
Yeah, he looks like
a substitute teacher.

406
00:19:40,846 --> 00:19:43,348
(boy laughing)

407
00:19:43,348 --> 00:19:47,853
(loud conversation
and laughter continues)

408
00:19:47,853 --> 00:19:49,855
Quiet down, people!

409
00:19:49,855 --> 00:19:52,357
My name is Mr. Abagnale!

410
00:19:52,357 --> 00:19:55,527
That's Abagnale,
not Abagnahlee

411
00:19:55,527 --> 00:19:59,031
not Abagnaylee,
but Abagnale!

412
00:19:59,031 --> 00:20:01,033
Now, somebody please
tell me where you left off

413
00:20:01,033 --> 00:20:03,035
in your textbooks.

414
00:20:04,536 --> 00:20:06,538
Excuse me, people,
if I need to ask again

415
00:20:06,538 --> 00:20:08,040
I'm going to write up
the entire class.

416
00:20:08,040 --> 00:20:10,542
Take your seats!

417
00:20:14,546 --> 00:20:16,048
Chapter seven.

418
00:20:16,048 --> 00:20:18,550
Will you please open your
textbooks to, uh, chapter eight

419
00:20:18,550 --> 00:20:21,053
and we'll get started?

420
00:20:21,053 --> 00:20:22,554
Excuse me,
what's your name?

421
00:20:22,554 --> 00:20:23,555
Brad.

422
00:20:23,555 --> 00:20:25,057
Brad, why don't you
get up here

423
00:20:25,557 --> 00:20:27,059
in front of the class here

424
00:20:27,059 --> 00:20:30,562
and read conversation
number five?

425
00:20:33,065 --> 00:20:36,068
(pronouncing poorly):
"Les Francais sonts

426
00:20:36,068 --> 00:20:38,070
"uh, generalement

427
00:20:38,070 --> 00:20:40,572
(students laughing)
"dans leur pais que...

428
00:20:40,572 --> 00:20:43,575
presque tout le monde
a cette impression..."

429
00:20:43,575 --> 00:20:45,077
They sent for me.

430
00:20:45,077 --> 00:20:48,080
They said they needed
a sub for Roberta.

431
00:20:48,080 --> 00:20:51,083
I came all the way
from-from Dixon.

432
00:20:51,083 --> 00:20:53,085
Well, uh,
I always sub for Roberta.

433
00:20:53,085 --> 00:20:55,587
Excuse me,
why aren't you reading?

434
00:20:55,587 --> 00:20:56,588
(continues reading)

435
00:20:56,588 --> 00:20:59,591
I'll never come back to-to
Bellarmine Jefferson again!

436
00:20:59,591 --> 00:21:02,094
(students laughing)
You tell them not to call me!

437
00:21:02,094 --> 00:21:04,596
What do they think,
it's easy for a woman my age

438
00:21:04,596 --> 00:21:06,598
and all the money that it costs
to travel?

439
00:21:06,598 --> 00:21:08,600
I tell you,
they don't give a damn.

440
00:21:08,600 --> 00:21:09,601
(students laughing)

441
00:21:09,601 --> 00:21:11,103
Mr. and Mrs. Abagnale

442
00:21:11,103 --> 00:21:14,606
this is not a question
of your son's attendance.

443
00:21:14,606 --> 00:21:17,609
I regret to inform you that,
for the past week

444
00:21:17,609 --> 00:21:21,113
Frank has been teaching
Mrs. Glasser's French class.

445
00:21:22,614 --> 00:21:24,116
He what?

446
00:21:24,116 --> 00:21:28,120
Your son has been pretending
to be a substitute teacher

447
00:21:28,120 --> 00:21:32,624
lecturing the students,
uh, giving out homework.

448
00:21:32,624 --> 00:21:36,128
Mrs. Glasser has
been ill and there was

449
00:21:36,128 --> 00:21:39,131
some confusion
with the real sub.

450
00:21:39,131 --> 00:21:42,634
Your son held a teacher-parent
conference yesterday

451
00:21:42,634 --> 00:21:45,137
and was planning
a class field trip

452
00:21:45,137 --> 00:21:47,639
to a French bread factory
in Trenton.

453
00:21:47,639 --> 00:21:51,143
Do you see the problem we have?

454
00:21:51,143 --> 00:21:53,145
Yeah.
Mrs. Davenport?

455
00:21:53,145 --> 00:21:55,647
Uh, I have a note
to miss fifth and
sixth period today.

456
00:21:55,647 --> 00:21:56,648
Doctor's appointment.

457
00:21:56,648 --> 00:21:58,650
One moment.
(phone ringing)

458
00:21:58,650 --> 00:22:00,152
I'll be right with you.

459
00:22:00,152 --> 00:22:01,153
(whispering):
Hey...

460
00:22:01,153 --> 00:22:02,154
MRS. DAVENPORT:
Yes?

461
00:22:02,154 --> 00:22:03,155
You should fold it.

462
00:22:03,155 --> 00:22:04,656
What?

463
00:22:04,656 --> 00:22:06,158
That note.
It's a fake, right?

464
00:22:06,158 --> 00:22:07,659
You should fold it.

465
00:22:07,659 --> 00:22:09,161
It's... It's a note
from my mom.

466
00:22:09,161 --> 00:22:11,163
I have a doctor's
appointment.

467
00:22:11,163 --> 00:22:13,665
Yeah, but there's
no crease in the paper.

468
00:22:14,166 --> 00:22:16,168
When your mom hands
you a note to miss school

469
00:22:16,168 --> 00:22:17,669
the first thing you do is,
you fold it

470
00:22:17,669 --> 00:22:19,171
and you put it
in your pocket.

471
00:22:19,171 --> 00:22:22,174
I mean, if it's real,
where's the crease?

472
00:22:27,179 --> 00:22:29,181
-(school bell ringing)
-(door opens)

473
00:22:32,184 --> 00:22:33,185
(quietly):
Frankie.

474
00:22:44,196 --> 00:22:47,699
(both chuckling quietly)

475
00:22:49,201 --> 00:22:51,203
Ma, I'm home.

476
00:22:51,203 --> 00:22:53,205
(romantic music
plays on record player)

477
00:22:53,205 --> 00:22:55,207
Oh, you remember
that girl Joanna

478
00:22:55,207 --> 00:22:57,209
I was telling you about?

479
00:22:57,209 --> 00:23:00,212
I asked her out today.

480
00:23:00,212 --> 00:23:02,714
Think we're going to go
to the Junior Prom.

481
00:23:02,714 --> 00:23:04,716
(record scratches,
music stops)

482
00:23:04,716 --> 00:23:06,718
Ma, is this
my driver's license?

483
00:23:06,718 --> 00:23:08,220
That's all there is,
two bedrooms.

484
00:23:08,220 --> 00:23:10,722
Oh, Frankie.

485
00:23:10,722 --> 00:23:12,724
You remember
Dad's friend?

486
00:23:12,724 --> 00:23:14,726
Jack Barnes?

487
00:23:14,726 --> 00:23:16,228
From the club.

488
00:23:16,228 --> 00:23:17,229
Hello.

489
00:23:17,229 --> 00:23:19,231
He came by looking
for your father.

490
00:23:19,231 --> 00:23:21,733
I was giving him
a tour of the apartment.

491
00:23:21,733 --> 00:23:24,736
It's very, uh, uh,
spacious, Paula.

492
00:23:30,242 --> 00:23:32,744
Dad's at the store.

493
00:23:32,744 --> 00:23:35,747
So, Frank... you're
getting to look

494
00:23:35,747 --> 00:23:38,750
more like your
old man every day.

495
00:23:41,253 --> 00:23:43,755
Thanks for the
sandwich, Paula.

496
00:23:43,755 --> 00:23:45,257
I'll see you later, eh?

497
00:23:45,257 --> 00:23:47,259
Wait.

498
00:23:51,763 --> 00:23:53,765
Is this yours?

499
00:23:53,765 --> 00:23:56,268
Oh.

500
00:23:56,768 --> 00:23:58,270
Well, thanks, Frank.

501
00:23:58,270 --> 00:24:00,772
Uh, that's
the President's pin.

502
00:24:00,772 --> 00:24:03,275
I'd be in deep trouble
if I lost that.

503
00:24:05,277 --> 00:24:07,279
(nervous chuckle)

504
00:24:09,281 --> 00:24:11,283
I'll see you all
later, eh?

505
00:24:20,792 --> 00:24:22,794
Are you hungry, Frankie?

506
00:24:22,794 --> 00:24:25,297
I'll make you a sandwich.

507
00:24:33,305 --> 00:24:36,308
Jack wanted to talk business
with your father.

508
00:24:36,308 --> 00:24:38,810
He thinks we should
get a lawyer

509
00:24:38,810 --> 00:24:40,812
and sue the government.

510
00:24:42,314 --> 00:24:45,317
That is not legal,
what they're doing to us.

511
00:24:48,320 --> 00:24:50,322
Why aren't you
saying anything?

512
00:24:56,828 --> 00:25:01,333
You're not going
to tell him... are you?

513
00:25:01,333 --> 00:25:02,834
(quietly):
No.

514
00:25:02,834 --> 00:25:04,336
That's right.

515
00:25:04,336 --> 00:25:06,838
There's nothing to tell.

516
00:25:07,339 --> 00:25:08,840
I'm going out
for a few hours

517
00:25:08,840 --> 00:25:11,843
to visit some old friends
from the tennis club and...

518
00:25:11,843 --> 00:25:15,347
when I get home, we'll all
have dinner together.

519
00:25:15,347 --> 00:25:17,349
Right?

520
00:25:17,349 --> 00:25:19,851
But you won't
say anything

521
00:25:19,851 --> 00:25:22,854
because it's...
it's just silly, isn't it?

522
00:25:22,854 --> 00:25:24,856
How could
we sue anybody?

523
00:25:28,860 --> 00:25:33,365
Oh... do you need
some money, Frankie?

524
00:25:33,365 --> 00:25:37,369
A few dollars to buy
some record albums?

525
00:25:37,369 --> 00:25:40,372
Here, take five dollars.

526
00:25:40,372 --> 00:25:42,374
Or-Or ten.

527
00:25:47,879 --> 00:25:49,881
You promised you
were going to quit.

528
00:25:49,881 --> 00:25:51,883
(slams)

529
00:25:55,387 --> 00:25:58,390
(children laughing)

530
00:25:58,390 --> 00:26:00,892
(dog barking in distance)

531
00:26:09,401 --> 00:26:11,403
Ma, I'm home!

532
00:26:21,413 --> 00:26:23,415
(door opens)

533
00:26:26,418 --> 00:26:27,919
Hey, hey!

534
00:26:27,919 --> 00:26:29,421
You... You stay away from me,
hear me?

535
00:26:29,421 --> 00:26:30,922
You stay away from me--
I don't know who you are

536
00:26:30,922 --> 00:26:32,424
but if you ever
come back here again--

537
00:26:32,424 --> 00:26:34,426
Frankie! Frank, Frank,
calm down, will you?

538
00:26:34,926 --> 00:26:35,927
I'm Dick Kesner.

539
00:26:35,927 --> 00:26:37,929
Now, I want you
to leave your things here

540
00:26:37,929 --> 00:26:40,432
and follow me
into the next room, okay?

541
00:26:40,432 --> 00:26:41,933
They're all waiting for you.

542
00:26:44,936 --> 00:26:46,938
PAULA:
You don't have
to be scared.

543
00:26:46,938 --> 00:26:48,940
I'm right here, Frank.
I'll always be here.

544
00:26:48,940 --> 00:26:50,942
But there are laws.

545
00:26:50,942 --> 00:26:52,944
Everything in this
country has to be legal.

546
00:26:52,944 --> 00:26:55,947
So what we need to do
is make some decisions.

547
00:26:55,947 --> 00:26:57,949
That's what Mr. Kesner
is here for.

548
00:26:57,949 --> 00:26:59,951
Many times these decisions
are left up to the courts

549
00:26:59,951 --> 00:27:01,453
but that can be
very expensive, Frank

550
00:27:01,453 --> 00:27:03,455
people fighting
over their children.

551
00:27:03,455 --> 00:27:04,956
Nobody is fighting.

552
00:27:04,956 --> 00:27:07,459
Look at me, Frank.
Nobody is fighting.

553
00:27:07,459 --> 00:27:09,961
(speaking French)

554
00:27:09,961 --> 00:27:12,464
(quietly):
Dad, what's going on?

555
00:27:12,464 --> 00:27:13,965
Dad, what's going on?

556
00:27:13,965 --> 00:27:16,468
(speaking French continues)

557
00:27:16,468 --> 00:27:18,303
Do you remember
your grandma, Eve?

558
00:27:18,303 --> 00:27:19,804
She arrived this morning.

559
00:27:19,804 --> 00:27:21,306
(speaks French)

560
00:27:21,306 --> 00:27:22,807
Hello.

561
00:27:31,316 --> 00:27:34,319
Do you understand what
we're saying to you, Frank?

562
00:27:36,321 --> 00:27:39,824
Your father and I
are getting a divorce.

563
00:27:40,325 --> 00:27:42,827
(speaking French)

564
00:27:42,827 --> 00:27:43,828
Nothing's gonna change.

565
00:27:43,828 --> 00:27:45,330
We're still gonna
see each other.

566
00:27:45,830 --> 00:27:47,332
Stop it, please, Frank.
Don't interrupt.

567
00:27:47,332 --> 00:27:49,834
Frank, you don't
have to read all of this.

568
00:27:49,834 --> 00:27:52,837
Most of it's for your parents--
boring adult business--

569
00:27:52,837 --> 00:27:55,840
but this paragraph right here,
this is important

570
00:27:55,840 --> 00:27:58,343
because it states
who you're gonna live with...

571
00:27:58,343 --> 00:28:00,345
after the divorce...

572
00:28:00,345 --> 00:28:02,347
whose custody you will be in.

573
00:28:02,347 --> 00:28:05,850
And there's a blank space
right here.

574
00:28:05,850 --> 00:28:06,851
(Eve speaking French)

575
00:28:06,851 --> 00:28:08,353
And I want you to go
into the kitchen

576
00:28:08,353 --> 00:28:09,854
sit at the table

577
00:28:09,854 --> 00:28:11,356
and put a name down.

578
00:28:11,356 --> 00:28:12,857
You can take
as long as you want

579
00:28:12,857 --> 00:28:14,359
but when you come back
into this room...

580
00:28:14,359 --> 00:28:16,861
I want to see a name
on that line.

581
00:28:17,362 --> 00:28:20,865
Frank, just write down a name
and this will all be over.

582
00:28:20,865 --> 00:28:22,867
It's gonna be okay.

583
00:28:22,867 --> 00:28:24,369
FRANK:
Dad, what name?

584
00:28:24,369 --> 00:28:25,870
Your mother or
your father.

585
00:28:25,870 --> 00:28:27,872
Just put the name there.
It's as simple as that.

586
00:28:27,872 --> 00:28:30,875
And don't look so scared.

587
00:28:30,875 --> 00:28:32,877
It's not a test.

588
00:28:32,877 --> 00:28:34,879
There's no wrong answer.

589
00:28:37,382 --> 00:28:40,385
(man announcing trains
 indistinctly)

590
00:28:43,388 --> 00:28:47,392
(melancholy jazz playing)

591
00:28:47,392 --> 00:28:48,393
Hi.

592
00:28:48,393 --> 00:28:49,894
(panting)

593
00:28:49,894 --> 00:28:51,396
One ticket to Grand
Central, please.

594
00:28:51,396 --> 00:28:54,399
That'll be $3.50, sir.

595
00:28:54,399 --> 00:28:57,402
Is it okay
if I write you a check?

596
00:29:02,407 --> 00:29:05,410
Carl, when do I get
to call my father?

597
00:29:05,410 --> 00:29:07,912
You can call him when
we get to New York.

598
00:29:07,912 --> 00:29:11,416
We leave for the airport
in seven hours.

599
00:29:11,416 --> 00:29:13,418
Until then, just sit there.

600
00:29:13,418 --> 00:29:16,421
Be quiet.

601
00:29:16,421 --> 00:29:18,423
You know, Carl,
on the other side of the hotel

602
00:29:18,423 --> 00:29:20,425
they got suites
that face the park.

603
00:29:21,426 --> 00:29:24,929
It's the best room
the FBI can afford.

604
00:29:26,931 --> 00:29:28,933
It's okay, I've stayed in worse.

605
00:29:29,434 --> 00:29:30,435
Mr. Mudrick...

606
00:29:30,435 --> 00:29:31,936
Mr. Mudrick, please.
You have to listen.

607
00:29:31,936 --> 00:29:33,438
I don't want to
hear your story.

608
00:29:33,938 --> 00:29:35,440
This is two checks
that bounced.

609
00:29:35,440 --> 00:29:37,442
You know how much
trouble I'm in?

610
00:29:37,442 --> 00:29:38,943
No, but listen,
I'm telling you

611
00:29:38,943 --> 00:29:39,944
the bank,
they made the mistake.

612
00:29:40,445 --> 00:29:41,946
I'll write you
another check right now!

613
00:29:41,946 --> 00:29:43,448
What, do I look like
I was born yesterday?

614
00:29:43,948 --> 00:29:45,450
Look, it's midnight,
Mr. Mudrick.

615
00:29:45,450 --> 00:29:46,451
Where am I gonna go?

616
00:29:46,451 --> 00:29:47,952
You're a goddamn kid.

617
00:29:48,453 --> 00:29:50,455
Go home.

618
00:29:51,956 --> 00:29:54,459
(baby crying in distance)

619
00:30:12,477 --> 00:30:16,981
? ?

620
00:30:26,357 --> 00:30:29,327
? ?

621
00:30:37,785 --> 00:30:39,287
I mean, I hope
you understand.

622
00:30:39,287 --> 00:30:40,788
My boss sent me to Brooklyn,
then Queens.

623
00:30:40,788 --> 00:30:42,290
Now he wants me
in Long Island

624
00:30:42,290 --> 00:30:44,792
to take a few clients out
for a night on the town.

625
00:30:44,792 --> 00:30:46,794
I'm sorry,
but we're not allowed

626
00:30:46,794 --> 00:30:48,296
to cash checks
from other banks.

627
00:30:48,296 --> 00:30:50,798
How would we know
if they were any good?

628
00:30:50,798 --> 00:30:52,300
What did you say
your name was?

629
00:30:52,300 --> 00:30:53,301
Ashley.

630
00:30:53,301 --> 00:30:54,802
Ashley...

631
00:30:54,802 --> 00:30:56,804
you know what I found on
the sidewalk out there?

632
00:31:02,310 --> 00:31:04,312
Must've slipped
right off your neck.

633
00:31:08,816 --> 00:31:12,820
Is there something
I can help you with, son?

634
00:31:12,820 --> 00:31:14,822
Well, you see, it's my
grandmother's birthday next week

635
00:31:15,323 --> 00:31:17,325
and I want to get her
something extra-special.

636
00:31:17,325 --> 00:31:18,826
Please, I mean

637
00:31:18,826 --> 00:31:21,329
it's my midterm next week
and my books were stolen.

638
00:31:21,329 --> 00:31:22,330
(raspy coughing)

639
00:31:22,330 --> 00:31:24,332
Please, it's just five dollars.

640
00:31:24,332 --> 00:31:25,833
No one would have to know.

641
00:31:25,833 --> 00:31:28,336
I'm sorry,
but we are not allowed

642
00:31:28,836 --> 00:31:31,839
to take checks
from people we don't know.

643
00:31:40,848 --> 00:31:42,850
(horns honking,
whistle blowing)

644
00:31:52,360 --> 00:31:55,863
? ?

645
00:32:05,373 --> 00:32:07,375
(women laughing)

646
00:32:13,881 --> 00:32:15,383
Pleasure to have you back,
Captain Carlson.

647
00:32:15,383 --> 00:32:16,884
What do you think, Angelo?

648
00:32:16,884 --> 00:32:18,386
The tomatoes are ripe
this afternoon.

649
00:32:18,886 --> 00:32:20,888
(women giggling)

650
00:32:26,394 --> 00:32:27,895
Well, what have we here?

651
00:32:27,895 --> 00:32:29,897
Can I have
your autograph?
You betcha.

652
00:32:29,897 --> 00:32:31,899
Can I have
your autograph, too?
You gonna be a pilot?

653
00:32:31,899 --> 00:32:33,901
Mm-hmm!
All right, then.

654
00:32:33,901 --> 00:32:35,403
There you go.
Work hard in school.

655
00:32:35,403 --> 00:32:36,904
FRANK:
Dear Dad:

656
00:32:36,904 --> 00:32:39,407
I have decided to become
an airline pilot.

657
00:32:39,407 --> 00:32:41,909
I have applied
to all the big airlines

658
00:32:41,909 --> 00:32:44,912
and I have several
promising interviews lined up.

659
00:32:44,912 --> 00:32:46,914
How's Mom?

660
00:32:46,914 --> 00:32:48,916
Have you called her lately?

661
00:32:48,916 --> 00:32:50,918
Love, your son, Frank.

662
00:32:54,422 --> 00:32:55,923
Hello.

663
00:32:55,923 --> 00:32:58,426
I'm Frank Black
from Murrow High School

664
00:32:58,426 --> 00:33:00,928
and I have an appointment
with Mr. Morgan.

665
00:33:00,928 --> 00:33:02,430
You're the young man

666
00:33:02,430 --> 00:33:04,432
who's writing the article
for the school paper.

667
00:33:04,432 --> 00:33:05,933
Yes, ma'am, that's me.
I want to know

668
00:33:05,933 --> 00:33:07,935
everything there is to know
about being a pilot.

669
00:33:07,935 --> 00:33:09,437
What airports
does Pan Am fly to?

670
00:33:09,437 --> 00:33:10,938
What does a pilot
make in a year?

671
00:33:10,938 --> 00:33:13,441
And who tells them where
they're gonna fly to?

672
00:33:13,441 --> 00:33:14,442
Whoa, whoa, whoa.
Slow down.

673
00:33:14,942 --> 00:33:15,943
Just take 'em
one at a time.

674
00:33:15,943 --> 00:33:16,944
All right.
What does it mean

675
00:33:16,944 --> 00:33:18,446
when one pilot says
to another pilot:

676
00:33:18,946 --> 00:33:20,448
"What kind of equipment
are you on?"

677
00:33:20,448 --> 00:33:22,950
They just want to
know what kind of
aircraft you're flying:

678
00:33:22,950 --> 00:33:24,452
Is it a DC-8, 707,
Constellation?

679
00:33:24,452 --> 00:33:26,954
And what about those I.D. badges
that I've seen pilots wear?

680
00:33:26,954 --> 00:33:29,457
Well, every pilot has
to have two things
with him at all times:

681
00:33:29,957 --> 00:33:31,459
One is his airline
personnel badge--

682
00:33:31,459 --> 00:33:33,461
looks just like this
one here, from Pan Am--

683
00:33:33,461 --> 00:33:35,963
the other one is
their FAA license...

684
00:33:35,963 --> 00:33:38,466
and that looks
just like this.

685
00:33:38,466 --> 00:33:40,468
Oh. Sir, do you
think I can

686
00:33:40,468 --> 00:33:43,971
make a copy of this
to put into my article?

687
00:33:43,971 --> 00:33:45,973
Oh, Frank, you can
have that one.

688
00:33:45,973 --> 00:33:46,974
It's three
years expired.

689
00:33:46,974 --> 00:33:48,976
Aw, thanks!
And what about
your I.D. badge?

690
00:33:48,976 --> 00:33:50,478
You have an extra
one I could borrow?

691
00:33:50,478 --> 00:33:52,480
Oh, no, I can't help you there.

692
00:33:52,480 --> 00:33:54,482
Those are special-ordered
from Polaroid.

693
00:33:54,482 --> 00:33:55,983
The only way
to get one of those

694
00:33:55,983 --> 00:33:58,486
is to become a real live pilot
for Pan American Airways.

695
00:33:58,486 --> 00:34:01,489
(dialing phone)

696
00:34:01,489 --> 00:34:02,990
(car horns honking,
whistle blowing)

697
00:34:02,990 --> 00:34:04,992
WOMAN (over phone):
Pan Am, may I help you?

698
00:34:04,992 --> 00:34:06,494
FRANK (Southern accent):
Yeah, hello.

699
00:34:06,494 --> 00:34:07,495
I'm calling about a uniform.

700
00:34:07,495 --> 00:34:08,996
Hold for Purchasing.

701
00:34:08,996 --> 00:34:09,997
Thank you.

702
00:34:09,997 --> 00:34:11,499
WOMAN 2:
Purchasing.

703
00:34:11,499 --> 00:34:13,501
(Southern accent):
Hi. I'm a copilot

704
00:34:13,501 --> 00:34:15,002
based out of San Francisco.

705
00:34:15,002 --> 00:34:16,504
I flew a flight
into New York last night

706
00:34:16,504 --> 00:34:17,505
but the problem is

707
00:34:18,005 --> 00:34:19,507
I'm headed out to, uh, Paris
in three hours.

708
00:34:19,507 --> 00:34:21,008
How can we help you?

709
00:34:21,509 --> 00:34:24,512
I sent my uniform to be cleaned
through the hotel

710
00:34:24,512 --> 00:34:27,014
and I... I guess
they must have lost it.

711
00:34:27,014 --> 00:34:29,517
WOMAN 2:
They lost a uniform.
Happens all the time.

712
00:34:29,517 --> 00:34:31,519
Go down to the Well-Built
Uniform Company

713
00:34:31,519 --> 00:34:32,520
at Ninth and Broadway.

714
00:34:32,520 --> 00:34:34,021
They're our uniform supplier.

715
00:34:34,021 --> 00:34:35,523
I'll tell Mr. Rosen
you're coming.

716
00:34:35,523 --> 00:34:38,025
ROSEN:
You look too young
to be a pilot.

717
00:34:38,025 --> 00:34:39,527
I'm a copilot.

718
00:34:39,527 --> 00:34:41,529
Why so nervous?

719
00:34:41,529 --> 00:34:43,030
How would you feel
if you, uh

720
00:34:43,030 --> 00:34:46,033
lost your uniform
first week on the job?

721
00:34:46,033 --> 00:34:47,535
Relax.

722
00:34:47,535 --> 00:34:50,037
Pan Am's got
lots of uniforms.

723
00:34:50,037 --> 00:34:52,540
It's gonna be $164.

724
00:34:52,540 --> 00:34:54,542
Great. I'll, uh,
I'll write you a check.

725
00:34:54,542 --> 00:34:56,544
Sorry, no checks,
no cash.

726
00:34:56,544 --> 00:34:59,046
You'll have to fill in
your employee I.D. number

727
00:34:59,046 --> 00:35:00,047
and then I'll
bill Pan Am.

728
00:35:00,047 --> 00:35:02,049
They'll take it out
of your next paycheck.

729
00:35:04,051 --> 00:35:06,053
Even better.

730
00:35:08,055 --> 00:35:10,057
FRANK:
Dear Dad:

731
00:35:10,057 --> 00:35:12,560
You always told me that an
honest man has nothing to fear.

732
00:35:12,560 --> 00:35:14,562
So I'm trying my best
not to be afraid.

733
00:35:15,062 --> 00:35:19,567
I'm sorry I ran away,
but you don't have to worry.

734
00:35:19,567 --> 00:35:21,569
I'm gonna get it all back
now, Daddy.

735
00:35:21,569 --> 00:35:24,071
I promise.
I'm going to get it all back.

736
00:35:24,071 --> 00:35:26,073
(approving murmur)

737
00:35:29,577 --> 00:35:31,579
GIRL:
Are you a real live pilot?

738
00:35:31,579 --> 00:35:33,581
I sure am, little lady.
What's your name?

739
00:35:34,081 --> 00:35:34,582
Celine.

740
00:35:35,082 --> 00:35:36,584
Celine, it's a
pleasure to meet you.

741
00:35:36,584 --> 00:35:39,086
It's a pleasure
to meet you, too.

742
00:35:42,590 --> 00:35:45,092
That's fifty, seventy

743
00:35:45,092 --> 00:35:49,096
eighty, ninety,
one hundred dollars.

744
00:35:49,096 --> 00:35:51,098
You have yourself a
great time in Paris.

745
00:35:51,098 --> 00:35:52,600
I always do.

746
00:35:52,600 --> 00:35:55,486
Excuse me.

747
00:35:55,987 --> 00:35:57,488
I'm John Modiger.
I manage this branch.

748
00:35:57,488 --> 00:35:58,990
I want to thank you
for coming in

749
00:35:58,990 --> 00:35:59,991
and using
our institution.

750
00:35:59,991 --> 00:36:01,993
Well, it's a pleasure
to meet you, John.

751
00:36:01,993 --> 00:36:02,994
I'll be back again.

752
00:36:02,994 --> 00:36:03,744
Good.

753
00:36:03,744 --> 00:36:05,496
Have you stayed with us before?

754
00:36:05,496 --> 00:36:09,000
Uh, no, I've been primarily
based on the West Coast.

755
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:12,503
Is it all right if I write
you a check for the room?

756
00:36:12,503 --> 00:36:13,504
No problem, sir.

757
00:36:13,504 --> 00:36:15,506
Great.

758
00:36:23,097 --> 00:36:24,015
Uh...

759
00:36:24,015 --> 00:36:25,016
I was also wondering

760
00:36:25,016 --> 00:36:27,018
if I could write you
a personal check?

761
00:36:27,018 --> 00:36:30,521
For airline personnel, we cash
personal checks up to $100.

762
00:36:30,521 --> 00:36:32,523
Payroll checks
we cash up to $300.

763
00:36:34,025 --> 00:36:36,527
Did you say $300
for a payroll check?

764
00:36:36,527 --> 00:36:39,030
(typewriter keys clacking)

765
00:36:41,532 --> 00:36:43,534
FRANK:
Dear Dad:

766
00:36:43,534 --> 00:36:46,537
I've decided to become a pilot
for Pan American Airways...

767
00:36:46,537 --> 00:36:49,540
the most trusted name
in the skies.

768
00:36:50,041 --> 00:36:52,543
They've accepted me
into their training program

769
00:36:52,543 --> 00:36:54,545
and told me that if I work hard

770
00:36:54,545 --> 00:36:56,047
I should earn my wings
real soon.

771
00:36:56,047 --> 00:36:58,549
Please get in touch with Joanna
Carlton from the tenth grade.

772
00:36:58,549 --> 00:37:02,053
Tell her I'm sorry that I could
not take her to the Junior Prom.

773
00:37:02,053 --> 00:37:04,055
Love, your son, Frank.

774
00:37:13,064 --> 00:37:16,067
? ?

775
00:37:26,077 --> 00:37:29,080
? ?

776
00:37:38,589 --> 00:37:40,591
? ?

777
00:37:43,094 --> 00:37:44,095
Hello, how are you?

778
00:37:44,095 --> 00:37:45,096
Fine, thank you.

779
00:37:45,096 --> 00:37:47,098
I have a payroll check here
I'd like to cash.

780
00:37:47,098 --> 00:37:49,100
Certainly.

781
00:37:49,100 --> 00:37:50,101
Thank you.

782
00:37:51,686 --> 00:37:53,104
Uh, excuse me.

783
00:37:53,104 --> 00:37:55,106
I'm sure you hear this
all the time

784
00:37:55,106 --> 00:37:57,108
but you have the most
beautiful eyes I have ever seen.

785
00:37:59,110 --> 00:38:00,611
Yeah, I do get
that all the time.

786
00:38:00,611 --> 00:38:02,613
(nervous laugh)

787
00:38:02,613 --> 00:38:04,115
How would you like it?

788
00:38:13,624 --> 00:38:16,627
? ?

789
00:38:19,130 --> 00:38:20,131
Oh, I'm sorry, sir.

790
00:38:20,631 --> 00:38:24,135
We won't have any cash until
the banks open in an hour

791
00:38:24,135 --> 00:38:25,636
but, uh, I'm sure

792
00:38:25,636 --> 00:38:28,139
they can cash your
check at the airport.

793
00:38:28,139 --> 00:38:29,640
The airport?

794
00:38:29,640 --> 00:38:32,143
Who cashes checks
at the airport?

795
00:38:32,143 --> 00:38:33,144
Well, the airlines, sir.

796
00:38:33,144 --> 00:38:35,646
They've always taken
care of their own.

797
00:38:35,646 --> 00:38:38,649
(jet passing overhead)

798
00:38:38,649 --> 00:38:41,652
(indistinct flight announcement
over P.A.)

799
00:38:44,155 --> 00:38:45,156
Hello.

800
00:38:45,656 --> 00:38:47,158
Hi. Are you deadheading?

801
00:38:47,158 --> 00:38:48,659
What?

802
00:38:48,659 --> 00:38:50,661
Are you my deadhead to Miami?

803
00:38:50,661 --> 00:38:53,164
Mi...?

804
00:38:53,164 --> 00:38:54,665
Yes, yes.

805
00:38:54,665 --> 00:38:55,666
(laughs)

806
00:38:55,666 --> 00:38:58,169
Yeah, I'm the deadhead.
Here you go.

807
00:38:58,169 --> 00:39:01,672
You're a little late,
but the jump seat is open.

808
00:39:03,674 --> 00:39:04,175
(chuckling):
You know

809
00:39:04,675 --> 00:39:06,177
it's been awhile
since I've done this.

810
00:39:06,177 --> 00:39:07,678
Which one's the
jump seat again?

811
00:39:07,678 --> 00:39:10,181
(both laughing)

812
00:39:10,181 --> 00:39:11,682
Have a nice flight.

813
00:39:11,682 --> 00:39:14,185
Are you my deadhead?

814
00:39:16,187 --> 00:39:18,189
STEWARDESS:
Frank, Captain Oliver.

815
00:39:18,189 --> 00:39:19,690
Hello.
John Larkin, the copilot.

816
00:39:19,690 --> 00:39:21,192
Fred Tulley,
flight engineer.

817
00:39:21,192 --> 00:39:22,193
Frank Taylor, Pan Am.

818
00:39:22,193 --> 00:39:24,195
Thanks for giving me
a lift, boys.

819
00:39:24,195 --> 00:39:25,696
Go ahead and take
a seat, Frank.

820
00:39:25,696 --> 00:39:27,198
We're about to push.

821
00:39:27,198 --> 00:39:29,200
What kind of
equipment you on, DC-8?

822
00:39:29,200 --> 00:39:31,202
Uh, 707.

823
00:39:31,202 --> 00:39:33,704
You turning around
on the redeye?

824
00:39:33,704 --> 00:39:35,706
Uh, I'm jumping puddles
for the next few months

825
00:39:35,706 --> 00:39:37,708
trying to earn my keep
running leapfrogs

826
00:39:37,708 --> 00:39:38,709
for the weak and weary.

827
00:39:38,709 --> 00:39:42,213
No shame in that.
We all did it.

828
00:39:48,719 --> 00:39:49,720
Have a seat.

829
00:39:49,720 --> 00:39:50,721
Thank you.

830
00:39:51,722 --> 00:39:53,724
Would you like a drink
after takeoff?

831
00:39:54,225 --> 00:39:55,726
M-Milk?

832
00:39:55,726 --> 00:39:57,228
OLIVER:
80 knots.

833
00:39:57,228 --> 00:39:58,229
LARKIN:
Check.

834
00:39:58,229 --> 00:39:59,730
V-one. Rotate.

835
00:39:59,730 --> 00:40:02,733
(jet engines roaring)

836
00:40:02,733 --> 00:40:04,735
V-two. Positive rate.

837
00:40:04,735 --> 00:40:06,737
Gear up.

838
00:40:07,238 --> 00:40:08,239
FRANK:
Dear Dad:

839
00:40:08,239 --> 00:40:09,740
Today was graduation.

840
00:40:09,740 --> 00:40:11,742
I am now a copilot

841
00:40:11,742 --> 00:40:14,745
earning $1,400 a month
plus benefits

842
00:40:14,745 --> 00:40:16,747
and the best part is

843
00:40:16,747 --> 00:40:19,250
they tell me
my family can fly for free.

844
00:40:19,250 --> 00:40:22,753
So tell Mom to pack her bags
and buy a new swimsuit

845
00:40:22,753 --> 00:40:25,756
because I'm taking us all
to Hawaii for Christmas.

846
00:40:25,756 --> 00:40:27,258
I love you, Dad.

847
00:40:27,258 --> 00:40:29,260
Aloha, Frank.

848
00:40:29,260 --> 00:40:30,761
Hello, deadhead.

849
00:40:30,761 --> 00:40:31,762
Hello.

850
00:40:31,762 --> 00:40:33,764
Enjoying your
free ride?

851
00:40:39,270 --> 00:40:42,273
Marci...

852
00:40:42,273 --> 00:40:44,275
did you drop this?

853
00:40:46,777 --> 00:40:48,279
Must've slipped
right off your neck.

854
00:40:48,779 --> 00:40:49,780
No...

855
00:40:49,780 --> 00:40:51,782
(chuckling)

856
00:40:51,782 --> 00:40:53,784
(giggling):
No!

857
00:40:53,784 --> 00:40:55,286
No...

858
00:40:55,286 --> 00:40:57,788
MARCI:
Yes, yes, yes, yes!

859
00:40:57,788 --> 00:41:00,791
(Frank moans passionately)

860
00:41:00,791 --> 00:41:01,792
Yes!

861
00:41:01,792 --> 00:41:03,794
(clanking and clattering)

862
00:41:03,794 --> 00:41:04,795
(Marci panting)

863
00:41:04,795 --> 00:41:08,799
Why are you stopping?

864
00:41:08,799 --> 00:41:12,303
I want to tell you
something, Marci.

865
00:41:12,303 --> 00:41:15,806
This is by far...

866
00:41:15,806 --> 00:41:20,811
the best date I
have ever been on.

867
00:41:20,811 --> 00:41:22,813
(laughing)

868
00:41:33,824 --> 00:41:35,826
? ?

869
00:41:40,331 --> 00:41:42,333
WOMAN:
I'd like to open a
Money Market, please.

870
00:41:42,333 --> 00:41:44,335
Okay.

871
00:41:50,341 --> 00:41:54,345
Welcome to Miami Mutual Bank.
How may I help you?

872
00:41:54,345 --> 00:41:57,848
My name is Frank Taylor.
I'm a copilot for Pan Am.

873
00:41:57,848 --> 00:42:00,851
I'd like to cash this check
here, and then

874
00:42:00,851 --> 00:42:03,854
I'd like to take you out
for a steak dinner.

875
00:42:04,855 --> 00:42:06,857
(laughing)

876
00:42:12,363 --> 00:42:13,864
(teller giggling)

877
00:42:13,864 --> 00:42:15,866
And then we feed the checks
into the MICR machine

878
00:42:15,866 --> 00:42:17,368
which uses special ink

879
00:42:17,368 --> 00:42:18,369
to encode the
account numbers

880
00:42:18,369 --> 00:42:19,870
on the bottom
of the checks.

881
00:42:21,372 --> 00:42:24,375
And where
are these numbers?

882
00:42:24,375 --> 00:42:26,377
They're, um...
right here.

883
00:42:26,377 --> 00:42:27,878
Right there?

884
00:42:27,878 --> 00:42:28,879
See?

885
00:42:28,879 --> 00:42:31,382
(both giggling)

886
00:42:31,382 --> 00:42:33,384
They're called
routing numbers.

887
00:42:33,384 --> 00:42:35,886
So where do the checks
get routed to?

888
00:42:36,887 --> 00:42:38,889
You know, I don't
exactly know.

889
00:42:38,889 --> 00:42:40,391
Nobody ever asked
me that before.

890
00:42:40,391 --> 00:42:42,393
(both laughing)

891
00:42:42,393 --> 00:42:43,894
AUCTIONEER:
Our next item up for bid

892
00:42:43,894 --> 00:42:46,397
is also from the Jersey
Central Bank foreclosure.

893
00:42:46,397 --> 00:42:47,398
This is a MICR encoder

894
00:42:47,398 --> 00:42:49,400
a machine used
to encode bank checks.

895
00:42:49,400 --> 00:42:50,401
Do I have an opening bid?

896
00:42:50,401 --> 00:42:52,403
HANRATTY:
Our unknown subject
is a paperhanger

897
00:42:52,403 --> 00:42:54,405
who started working
on the East Coast.

898
00:42:54,405 --> 00:42:56,407
In the last few weeks,
this unsub has developed

899
00:42:56,407 --> 00:42:58,909
a new form of check fraud
which I'm calling "the float."

900
00:42:58,909 --> 00:43:00,411
What he's doing is

901
00:43:00,411 --> 00:43:02,413
he's opening checking accounts
at various banks

902
00:43:02,413 --> 00:43:03,914
then changing the MICR ink
routing numbers

903
00:43:03,914 --> 00:43:05,416
at the bottom of those checks.

904
00:43:05,416 --> 00:43:06,917
Next slide, please.

905
00:43:06,917 --> 00:43:07,918
(projector clanks)

906
00:43:07,918 --> 00:43:09,920
Next slide, please.

907
00:43:09,920 --> 00:43:11,422
Uh, the remote
thing is broken.

908
00:43:11,422 --> 00:43:12,923
You'll have to
do it by hand.

909
00:43:12,923 --> 00:43:13,924
You've gotta...
try the...

910
00:43:13,924 --> 00:43:15,426
Agent Mullen,
it should be...

911
00:43:15,426 --> 00:43:18,429
it should be the square button
just there by the side.

912
00:43:18,429 --> 00:43:19,430
This carousel doesn't work.

913
00:43:19,430 --> 00:43:20,931
It's a bad carousel
you got there.

914
00:43:20,931 --> 00:43:21,932
Thank you,
Agent Mullen.

915
00:43:21,932 --> 00:43:23,434
Got to move
it manually.

916
00:43:23,434 --> 00:43:25,936
This is a map of the 12 banks
of the U.S. Federal Reserve.

917
00:43:25,936 --> 00:43:27,938
Slide.

918
00:43:27,938 --> 00:43:28,939
(clicking)

919
00:43:28,939 --> 00:43:30,441
MICR scanners at every bank

920
00:43:30,441 --> 00:43:32,943
read these numbers
at the bottom of a check--

921
00:43:32,943 --> 00:43:33,944
slide--

922
00:43:33,944 --> 00:43:37,448
and then, ship that check off
to its corresponding branch.

923
00:43:37,448 --> 00:43:39,950
Carl, for those of us who are
unfamiliar with bank fraud

924
00:43:40,451 --> 00:43:42,453
you mind telling us
what the hell

925
00:43:42,453 --> 00:43:43,954
you're talking about?

926
00:43:43,954 --> 00:43:47,958
The East Coast branches are
numbered zero-one to zero-six.

927
00:43:47,958 --> 00:43:49,960
The central branch
is zero-seven, zero-eight

928
00:43:49,960 --> 00:43:50,961
so on, so forth.

929
00:43:50,961 --> 00:43:52,963
You mean those numbers
on the bottom of a check

930
00:43:52,963 --> 00:43:53,964
actually mean something?

931
00:43:53,964 --> 00:43:54,965
All of this
was in the report

932
00:43:54,965 --> 00:43:56,467
I filed two days ago.

933
00:43:56,467 --> 00:44:00,471
If you change...
a zero-two to a one-two

934
00:44:00,471 --> 00:44:03,474
that means that check,
which was cashed in New York

935
00:44:03,474 --> 00:44:04,975
does not go to the New York
Federal Branch

936
00:44:04,975 --> 00:44:06,477
but it is rerouted

937
00:44:06,477 --> 00:44:09,480
all the way to the San Francisco
Federal Branch.

938
00:44:09,480 --> 00:44:12,483
The bank doesn't even know the
check has bounced for two weeks

939
00:44:12,483 --> 00:44:14,485
which means our unsub
can stay in one place

940
00:44:14,485 --> 00:44:15,986
paper the same city
over and over again

941
00:44:15,986 --> 00:44:17,738
while his checks
circle the country.

942
00:44:17,738 --> 00:44:20,991
You know, you want
to talk to my wife.

943
00:44:20,991 --> 00:44:23,994
She's the one balances
the checkbook at our house.

944
00:44:23,994 --> 00:44:26,497
(agents laughing)

945
00:44:28,332 --> 00:44:30,834
Next slide.

946
00:44:30,834 --> 00:44:36,340
(three-piece combo
plays soft jazz)

947
00:44:36,340 --> 00:44:37,841
Daddy!

948
00:44:37,841 --> 00:44:38,842
(chuckling)

949
00:44:40,844 --> 00:44:42,846
My son, the birdman.

950
00:44:42,846 --> 00:44:43,847
Some uniform, Frank.

951
00:44:43,847 --> 00:44:45,849
What do you think?

952
00:44:45,849 --> 00:44:47,351
Nice.

953
00:44:47,351 --> 00:44:48,852
Sit down.

954
00:44:48,852 --> 00:44:50,354
(clears throat)

955
00:44:51,855 --> 00:44:54,358
So, Dad... Daddy, have you
gotten the postcards?

956
00:44:54,358 --> 00:44:55,359
Of course.

957
00:44:55,359 --> 00:44:57,861
This fork is ice cold.

958
00:44:57,861 --> 00:45:01,365
No, no, Dad, th-that's
a chilled salad fork.

959
00:45:01,365 --> 00:45:06,370
(whispering):
It's a fancy restaurant,
you know.

960
00:45:06,370 --> 00:45:09,373
(sighing)

961
00:45:09,373 --> 00:45:11,875
Well, here...

962
00:45:11,875 --> 00:45:13,877
I-I got you something.

963
00:45:13,877 --> 00:45:15,713
What's that?

964
00:45:15,713 --> 00:45:17,715
Open it.

965
00:45:21,719 --> 00:45:23,721
You know what
those are, right?

966
00:45:23,721 --> 00:45:25,723
Those are the keys

967
00:45:25,723 --> 00:45:28,726
to a 1965 Cadillac
DeVille convertible.

968
00:45:28,726 --> 00:45:30,227
Brand-new, Dad.

969
00:45:30,227 --> 00:45:33,230
Red with white interior

970
00:45:33,230 --> 00:45:37,735
split seats,
air conditioning, the works.

971
00:45:37,735 --> 00:45:38,736
Are you giving me
a Cadillac?

972
00:45:38,736 --> 00:45:40,738
Yeah. I'm giving you
a Cadillac.

973
00:45:40,738 --> 00:45:42,239
Dad, sh-she's parked
downstairs.

974
00:45:42,239 --> 00:45:43,741
When we're done
eating lunch

975
00:45:43,741 --> 00:45:46,744
why don't you, you know,
drive on over to Mom's house

976
00:45:46,744 --> 00:45:48,746
pick her up,
take a little joyride?

977
00:45:48,746 --> 00:45:50,748
Do you know what
would happen

978
00:45:50,748 --> 00:45:52,249
if the IRS found out

979
00:45:52,249 --> 00:45:55,753
I was driving around
in a new coupe?

980
00:45:55,753 --> 00:45:57,755
I took the train
here, Frank.

981
00:45:57,755 --> 00:46:00,257
I'm taking the train home.

982
00:46:01,759 --> 00:46:03,761
All right.

983
00:46:08,766 --> 00:46:11,769
I have plenty of money.

984
00:46:12,269 --> 00:46:14,271
You know, if you
ever, ever need anything...

985
00:46:14,271 --> 00:46:15,773
You worried?

986
00:46:15,773 --> 00:46:18,025
About me?

987
00:46:18,025 --> 00:46:19,777
No, I'm not...
I'm not worried.

988
00:46:19,777 --> 00:46:22,029
You think I can't
buy my own car?

989
00:46:22,396 --> 00:46:26,784
Two mice fell in a
bucket of cream, Frank.

990
00:46:26,784 --> 00:46:28,786
Which one am I?

991
00:46:28,786 --> 00:46:31,288
You're that second mouse.

992
00:46:33,290 --> 00:46:36,794
I went by the store today.

993
00:46:36,794 --> 00:46:38,796
I had to close the
store for awhile.

994
00:46:38,796 --> 00:46:40,297
It's all about
timing, Frank.

995
00:46:40,297 --> 00:46:42,299
The goddamn government
knows that.

996
00:46:42,299 --> 00:46:43,801
They hit you
when you're down.

997
00:46:43,801 --> 00:46:44,802
I wasn't going
to let them

998
00:46:45,302 --> 00:46:46,804
take it from me,
so I just...

999
00:46:46,804 --> 00:46:49,306
shut the doors myself,
called their bluff.

1000
00:46:54,311 --> 00:46:56,313
Sooner or later,
they'll forget about me.

1001
00:46:56,313 --> 00:46:58,816
I understand, I...

1002
00:46:58,816 --> 00:47:02,319
Have you told Ma?

1003
00:47:03,821 --> 00:47:08,325
She's so stubborn, your mother.

1004
00:47:11,328 --> 00:47:12,329
Don't worry.

1005
00:47:12,329 --> 00:47:14,832
I'm not going to let her go
without a fight.

1006
00:47:14,832 --> 00:47:15,833
I been fighting for us...

1007
00:47:16,333 --> 00:47:17,334
(gasps quietly)

1008
00:47:18,836 --> 00:47:20,337
Dad?

1009
00:47:22,840 --> 00:47:25,342
...since the day we... we met.

1010
00:47:25,342 --> 00:47:27,344
Daddy, out of all those men

1011
00:47:27,344 --> 00:47:30,347
you were the one that
took her home, remember that.

1012
00:47:30,848 --> 00:47:33,851
200 men, sitting in
that tiny social hall

1013
00:47:33,851 --> 00:47:35,853
watching her dance.

1014
00:47:38,355 --> 00:47:40,858
What was the name of that town?

1015
00:47:40,858 --> 00:47:42,359
Montrichard, Dad.

1016
00:47:42,359 --> 00:47:43,861
Yeah.

1017
00:47:43,861 --> 00:47:46,864
I didn't speak
a word of French

1018
00:47:46,864 --> 00:47:50,367
and six weeks later,
she was my wi...

1019
00:47:50,367 --> 00:47:53,370
She's your wife.

1020
00:47:53,370 --> 00:47:57,374
My son bought me
a Cadillac today.

1021
00:47:57,374 --> 00:48:01,378
I think that calls for a toast.

1022
00:48:01,378 --> 00:48:02,880
(soft jazz playing)

1023
00:48:05,883 --> 00:48:08,886
(inhaling deeply)

1024
00:48:08,886 --> 00:48:12,389
To the best damn pilot
in the sky.

1025
00:48:12,389 --> 00:48:13,891
It's not
what you think.

1026
00:48:13,891 --> 00:48:16,894
I'm just a copilot.

1027
00:48:16,894 --> 00:48:20,397
You see these people
staring at you?

1028
00:48:23,400 --> 00:48:25,402
These are the most
powerful people

1029
00:48:25,402 --> 00:48:26,904
in New York City

1030
00:48:26,904 --> 00:48:29,406
and they keep peeking
over their shoulders

1031
00:48:29,406 --> 00:48:31,408
wondering where
you're going tonight.

1032
00:48:31,408 --> 00:48:32,910
Where you going, Frank?

1033
00:48:32,910 --> 00:48:36,413
Dad, nobody's
staring at me.

1034
00:48:36,413 --> 00:48:38,415
Some place exotic?

1035
00:48:40,918 --> 00:48:43,420
Just tell me where you're going.

1036
00:48:44,922 --> 00:48:47,424
Los An... Hollywood.

1037
00:48:47,424 --> 00:48:49,927
Hollywood.

1038
00:48:51,929 --> 00:48:54,932
(sniffles)

1039
00:48:54,932 --> 00:48:56,934
(whispering):
The rest of us...

1040
00:48:56,934 --> 00:48:59,937
really are suckers.

1041
